 no access control even though it triggers the privileged `from_bank.issue(address(this), amount)` flow and then transfers the swapped proceeds to `to_bank`. Any external account can therefore force arbitrary migrations out of `from_bank` up to its reported balance.","impact":"A third party can permissionlessly deplete the source bank's liquid backing and choose the timing of those migrations. Even without profiting directly, this can exhaust `from_bank` liquidity, break redemptions or issuance assumptions tied to that bank, and create a protocol-level denial of service or insolvency condition if liabilities remain associated with `from_bank`.","paths":["Attacker watches `from_bank.balance()` until meaningful liquidity is available.","Attacker repeatedly calls `doExchange()` with amounts up to the current reported balance.","Each call forces `from_bank.issue(...)` and moves the resulting value away from `from_bank` into `to_bank` without any operator or owner authorization."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Swapped funds are sent to `to_bank` via raw ERC20 transfer with no deposit/accounting handshake","source_agents":["codex_1"],"reason":"Speculative. The available source only shows a raw token transfer into `to_bank`; there is no evidence that the destination bank requires an explicit deposit hook or that passive ERC20 receipt is insufficient for its accounting."},{"title":"Unchecked return value from external token bank balance call","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Not a standalone vulnerability in this code. It relies on a malicious or broken `from_bank` dependency returning false data, which is outside the demonstrated trust model."},{"title":"Constructor makes unsafe external calls without try-catch","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"A constructor reverting on bad parameters or incompatible external contracts is expected deployment-time behavior, not a reportable protocol vulnerability."},{"title":"No validation of exchange output amount before transfer","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Duplicate of the missing slippage protection issue. The lack of `min_dy` already captures the harmful acceptance of arbitrarily poor output."},{"title":"Hardcoded Curve pool address creates centralization risk","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Operational rigidity / maintainability concern, but not a concrete exploitable vulnerability causing protocol-level harm on its own."},{"title":"No event logging for doExchange execution","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Observability issue only; not a security finding."},{"title":"Potential reentrancy vulnerability in safeApprove pattern","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Unsupported. The function has no sensitive intermediate state to exploit via reentrancy, and the report depends on a malicious Curve/token assumption not evidenced here."},{"title":"Unused SafeMath library functions in main contract","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Code quality issue only; not a security vulnerability."},{"title":"No deadline parameter in exchange function","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Not a distinct vulnerability here. The meaningful economic risk is already covered by the missing slippage protection, and the function is permissionless rather than user-order driven."}]}
